byshire, England, United Kingdom","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Heathcote","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Heathcote in Hartington (Derbyshire), Heathcote in Warwick (Warwickshire), or Heathcote Farm in Wasperton (Warwickshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’. In Yorkshire, this name is pronounced <i>Hethkett</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hathcoat","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Heathcote  ."]},{"name":"Heathcott","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Lancashire): variant of   Heathcote  ."]},{"name":"Heathcoat","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Heathcote  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Richard Heathcote was born in 1410, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons with Rose Seahorse. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1410–":"1410–Surnud","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1440–1492":"1440–1492","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1415":"1415","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"umbes 1430","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1410–":"1410–Kuollut","1415–Female":"1415–Kuollut","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1440–1492":"1440–1492","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"noin 1430","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"1410–":"1410–Décédé","1415–Female":"1415–Décédée","1430–Male":"1430–Décédé","1440–1492":"1440–1492","1410–Male":"1410–Décédé","1415":"1415","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"environ 1430","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1492":"1492","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir Richard Heat